 alpaca and Peruvian civilizations, drawing on traditional knowledge in order to exist in harmony with our environment, even in this modern world. We seek to return to the natural and explore more sustainable ways of living, manufacturing and discovering the world around us.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-f81a" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dkYRCH cfhJKO pf-111_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-dtDOqo lfZCLK"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-112_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-113_"><p class="sc-eGPXGI dCeUID pf-114_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-116_">It is said that the study of history helps us to better understand the world in which we live, so we delved into the long past of the alpaca, to see what we could find out.</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-f96e" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dkYRCH cfhJKO pf-117_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-dtDOqo lfZCLK"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-118_ pf-r pf-c-cm" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-119_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-120_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-122_"><span style="font-weight: normal;">45-40 MILLION YEARS AGO</span></span></h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-123_ pf-bg-lazy"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-125_">Origin of the Species</span></h3><p class="sc-eGPXGI dCeUID pf-126_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-128_">Alpacas are a domesticated member of the Camelidae family, which first appeared in North America 45-40 million years ago. Over millions of years, two camelid tribes emerged from the Protylopus, (the modern camelid's common ancestor): the Camelini and Lamini. Members of the Camelini tribe headed east, to Asia and Africa, while the Lamini family moved south, towards South America.&nbsp;<br></span></p></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-129_ pf-bg-lazy"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-291ae3d9--Bactrian-camel-in-a-snowy-desert_500x.jpg?v=1607615625" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-291ae3d9--Bactrian-camel-in-a-snowy-desert.jpg?v=1607615625 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-291ae3d9--Bactrian-camel-in-a-snowy-desert_1500x.jpg?v=1607615625 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-291ae3d9--Bactrian-camel-in-a-snowy-desert_1000x.jpg?v=1607615625 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-291ae3d9--Bactrian-camel-in-a-snowy-desert_500x.jpg?v=1607615625 320w" width="1800" height="1012" sizes="(min-width: 1536px) 1536px, (min-width: 1024px) 1280px, (min-width: 640px) 768px, 320px" loading="lazy" alt="Bactrian camel in the snowy desert" title="Camels have the same common ancestor as the alpaca" data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-jQrDum igoalK pf-130_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-9025" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dkYRCH cfhJKO pf-131_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-dtDOqo lfZCLK"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-132_ pf-r pf-c-cm" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-133_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-134_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-136_"><span style="font-weight: normal;">5-2 MILLION YEARS AGO</span></span></h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-137_ pf-bg-lazy"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-139_">Alpaca's Closest Cousin</span></h3><p class="sc-eGPXGI dCeUID pf-140_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-142_">The Lamini genus Hemiauchenia, migrated to South America about 2-5 million years ago, splitting into Palaeolama and Lama tribes. The Lama tribe then split into a further two groups: <span style="font-weight: bold;">Vicuña </span>and <span style="font-weight: bold;">Guanaco</span>. Both still live in the Andes today, the former mostly in Bolivia, Peru and Northern Chile, the latter in Patagonia. The vicuña is prized for its incredibly fine, luxurious fiber, but the species didn't react well to domestication, so now vicuña roam wild and are a protected species in some places.<br></span></p></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-143_ pf-bg-lazy"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-e3d92f0f--vicuna-in-mountainous-terrain-looking-at-the-camera_500x.jpg?v=1607615635" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-e3d92f0f--vicuna-in-mountainous-terrain-looking-at-the-camera.jpg?v=1607615635 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-e3d92f0f--vicuna-in-mountainous-terrain-looking-at-the-camera_1500x.jpg?v=1607615635 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-e3d92f0f--vicuna-in-mountainous-terrain-looking-at-the-camera_1000x.jpg?v=1607615635 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-e3d92f0f--vicuna-in-mountainous-terrain-looking-at-the-camera_500x.jpg?v=1607615635 320w" width="1800" height="1012" sizes="(min-width: 1536px) 1536px, (min-width: 1024px) 1280px, (min-width: 640px) 768px, 320px" loading="lazy" alt="a lone vicuña standing in the high altitude desert" title="The vicuña is the alpaca's closest ancestor" data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-jQrDum igoalK pf-144_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-908a" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dkYRCH cfhJKO pf-145_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-dtDOqo lfZCLK"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-146_ pf-r pf-c-cm" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-147_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-148_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-150_"><span style="font-weight: normal;">5000-500 YEARS AGO</span></span></h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-151_ pf-bg-lazy"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-153_">Domestication &amp; The Inca Empire<br></span></h3><p class="sc-eGPXGI dCeUID pf-154_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-156_">Evidence shows that the alpaca was domesticated from the wild vicuña and indicates that they have been bred for over 5,000 years. Smaller than the llama, which was domesticated for use as a cargo animal, the alpaca was bred for its soft, luxurious fiber. During the time of the Inca, alpaca wool was used to make clothing for royalty and was know as "The Fiber of the Gods".<br></span></p></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-157_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-ffdf39a8--machu-picchu-pinacle-of-inca-empire_500x.jpg?v=1607906394" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-ffdf39a8--machu-picchu-pinacle-of-inca-empire.jpg?v=1607906394 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-ffdf39a8--machu-picchu-pinacle-of-inca-empire_1500x.jpg?v=1607906394 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-ffdf39a8--machu-picchu-pinacle-of-inca-empire_1000x.jpg?v=1607906394 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-ffdf39a8--machu-picchu-pinacle-of-inca-empire_500x.jpg?v=1607906394 320w" width="2536" height="1426" sizes="(min-width: 1536px) 1536px, (min-width: 1024px) 1280px, (min-width: 640px) 768px, 320px" loading="lazy" alt="view over Machu Picchu and Huayna Picchu Mountain" title="The Inca quickly built incredible cities on difficult terrain" data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-jQrDum igoalK pf-158_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-8a90" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dkYRCH cfhJKO pf-159_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-dtDOqo lfZCLK"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-160_ pf-r pf-c-cm" style="--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-161_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-162_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-164_"><span style="font-weight: normal;">500 YEARS AGO</span></span></h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-165_ pf-bg-lazy"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-167_">The Spanish Conquest<br></span></h3><p class="sc-eGPXGI dCeUID pf-168_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-170_">The story of the alpaca took a turbulent turn when Spanish forces invaded Inca territories in 1532, starting the decimation of the Inca Empire. The invaders grossly underestimated the value of alpaca fiber, so they used alpaca for meat and replaced them with sheep and cattle. The alpaca might have vanished from history completely, were it not for those who managed to retreat into the mountains with their animals, keeping the alpaca gene pool alive.<br></span></p></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-171_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-11d2685a--mural-of-spanish-conquest-in-peru_500x.jpg?v=1607905237" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-11d2685a--mural-of-spanish-conquest-in-peru.jpg?v=1607905237 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-11d2685a--mural-of-spanish-conquest-in-peru_1500x.jpg?v=1607905237 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-11d2685a--mural-of-spanish-conquest-in-peru_1000x.jpg?v=1607905237 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-11d2685a--mural-of-spanish-conquest-in-peru_500x.jpg?v=1607905237 320w" width="1500" height="843" sizes="(min-width: 1536px) 1536px, (min-width: 1024px) 1280px, (min-width: 640px) 768px, 320px" loading="lazy" alt="Mural depicting the Spanish conquest of the city of Cusco" title="The Spanish Conquest of the Inca Empire, depicted by a mural in Cusco" data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-jQrDum igoalK pf-172_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-e963" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dkYRCH cfhJKO pf-173_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-dtDOqo lfZCLK"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-174_ pf-r pf-c-cm" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-175_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-176_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-178_"><span style="font-weight: normal;">19th to 20th CENTURY</span></span></h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-179_ pf-bg-lazy"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-181_">The Revival of Alpaca<br></span></h3><p class="sc-eGPXGI dCeUID pf-182_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-184_">A few centuries later, alpaca fiber starting gaining prominence again, this time in England. Historians note that alpaca wool was taken there in the early 1800s, but it was condemned as an unworkable material. It was not until 1836 that a man called Titus Salt revealed the true qualities of alpaca wool. After months of experimentation, he was able to work it into a soft, lustrous cloth and presented a gown made from alpaca wool to Queen Victoria, drastically increasing demand for and interest in this special fiber.  <br></span></p></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-185_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-97291ae3--alpacas-roaming-free-in-field_500x.jpg?v=1607615620" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-97291ae3--alpacas-roaming-free-in-field.jpg?v=1607615620 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-97291ae3--alpacas-roaming-free-in-field_1500x.jpg?v=1607615620 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-97291ae3--alpacas-roaming-free-in-field_1000x.jpg?v=1607615620 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-97291ae3--alpacas-roaming-free-in-field_500x.jpg?v=1607615620 320w" width="1800" height="1012" sizes="(min-width: 1536px) 1536px, (min-width: 1024px) 1280px, (min-width: 640px) 768px, 320px" loading="lazy" alt="Two white alpacas in a highland field of ichu grass" title="Alpaca thrive again throughout the Andes" data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-jQrDum igoalK pf-186_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-95b8" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dkYRCH cfhJKO pf-187_ pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-dtDOqo lfZCLK"><div class="sc-ezbkAF A-dmbO pf-188_ pf-r pf-c-cm" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-189_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-190_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-192_"><span style="font-weight: normal;">THE 21st CENTURY</span></span></h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu eBgidd pf-193_ pf-bg-lazy"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-195_">Alpaca Today<br></span></h3><p class="sc-eGPXGI dCeUID pf-196_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gUQvok zBuIu pf-198_">These days, alpaca can be found around the world, but thrive in their natural habitat: the Peruvian Andes. Alpaca are usually raised in small herds, by individual families, in remote, mountainous terrain. Highland communities still have traditional lifestyles, so their farming methods are based on ancestral knowledge and are generally more sustainable than most modern farming practices. Over the centuries, the gene pool of the alpaca has become less pure, especially due to mixing with llamas, but more projects are focused on improving the purity of alpaca types  and colors, especially black, a bloodline that had verged on extinction.</span></p></div></div><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-brSvTw iyWbaU pf-199_"><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-2f5e8f35--alpaca-herder-in-the-mountains-with-her-flock-smaller_500x.jpg?v=1607630919" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-2f5e8f35--alpaca-herder-in-the-mountains-with-her-flock-smaller.jpg?v=1607630919 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-2f5e8f35--alpaca-herder-in-the-mountains-with-her-flock-smaller_1500x.jpg?v=1607630919 1280w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-2f5e8f35--alpaca-herder-in-the-mountains-with-her-flock-smaller_1000x.jpg?v=1607630919 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0071/4748/7305/t/11/assets/pf-2f5e8f35--alpaca-herder-in-the-mountains-with-her-flock-smaller_500x.jpg?v=1607630919 320w" width="1800" height="1012" sizes="(min-width: 